Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 17-A MRSA §18-A is enacted to read:
3 §18-A. Anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation protocol
4 A person who a law enforcement officer has reason to believe is experiencing or has
5 experienced human trafficking or commercial sexual exploitation must be treated in
6 accordance with the anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation protocol,
7 referred to in this section as "the protocol," adopted by the responding law enforcement
8 agency under subsection 2.
9 1. Law enforcement agency; definition. As used in this section, unless the context
10 otherwise indicates, "law enforcement agency" has the same meaning as in Title 25, section
11 3701, subsection 1.
12 2. Adoption of anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation protocol.
13 This subsection governs the adoption of anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual
14 exploitation protocols by law enforcement agencies. An anti-sex-trafficking and
15 commercial sexual exploitation protocol must include information on anti-trafficking
16 organizations; sexual assault organizations; domestic violence victim advocacy
17 organizations; crisis services; mental health and substance use disorder professionals;
18 emergency and transitional housing; and case management services.
19 A. By January 1, 2026, the Department of Public Safety shall consult with relevant
20 stakeholders, including anti-trafficking organizations, sexual assault organizations,
21 domestic violence victim advocacy organizations and crisis services, to adopt a model
22 anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation protocol. Rules adopted
23 pursuant to this paragraph are routine technical rules as defined by Title 5, chapter 375,
24 subchapter 2‑A.
25 B. By March 1, 2026, all law enforcement agencies shall adopt anti-sex-trafficking
26 and commercial sexual exploitation protocols. The protocol of a law enforcement
27 agency may, but is not required to, conform to the protocol adopted by the Department
28 of Public Safety.
29 3. Law enforcement response to victim of human trafficking or commercial
30 sexual exploitation. A law enforcement officer who responds to a call regarding or
31 encounters a person who the law enforcement officer has reason to believe is experiencing
32 or has experienced human trafficking or commercial sexual exploitation shall inquire
33 whether the person is experiencing or has experienced human trafficking or commercial
34 sexual exploitation. If the person affirms as experiencing or having experienced human
35 trafficking or commercial sexual exploitation, the law enforcement officer shall respond to
36 the person using the anti-sex-trafficking and commercial sexual exploitation protocol
37 adopted by the officer's law enforcement agency as required under subsection 2.
38 SUMMARY
3399 This bill directs the Department of Public Safety to adopt a model protocol for law
4400 enforcement agencies to adopt to treat a person who is experiencing or has experienced
4411 human trafficking or commercial sexual exploitation.
